Legal Calculus represents my commitment to the legal profession—an open, procedural educational system aimed at enhancing access to justice for self-represented litigants.

Every day, courts encounter individuals who face disadvantages not due to the merit of their claims, but because of a lack of procedural knowledge. These litigants struggle with formatting, deadlines, evidentiary preservation, and the intricacies of motion practice. These challenges are not failures of character; they are failures of access.

Legal Calculus was developed to bridge that gap.

It is not legal advice.  

It is not representation.  

It is not a substitute for counsel.  

It is **public legal education**: a structured and transparent framework designed to teach self-represented litigants how to navigate procedures responsibly—how to create a coherent record, preserve evidence, and interact with the court in a manner that promotes judicial efficiency.

Legal professionals understand that a clean record, properly formatted filings, and procedurally literate litigants enhance the system for everyone—judges, clerks, opposing counsel, and the public.

Legal Calculus aims to support this ecosystem.

I believe that by empowering the disadvantaged with procedural knowledge, we can reduce chaos, enhance fairness, and strengthen the legitimacy of the institutions we serve.

This is my contribution to a justice system that serves not only the well-resourced but everyone.